<TITLE> BNP sticks with 'temporary' boycott </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 1 (bdnews24.com) - The main opposition BNP and its allies are sticking to their "temporary" boycott of parliament until the speaker's decision over seating order. "The speaker rearranged the seating in parliament ... After we informed him of our stance on the matter, he said he would convey his decision to us," senior BNP MP Salauddin Quader Chowdhury said after a meeting of the party's MPs. "As we are yet to get any decision from the speaker, we are temporarily abstaining from joining parliament," he said. "As we are yet to get any decision from the speaker, we are temporarily abstaining from joining parliament," he said. The opposition MPs met earlier in the day to decide whether they would rejoin the House during Sunday's sitting, opposition chief whip Joynal Abdin Faruk told bdnews24.com. Two Jamaat-e-Islami MPs also attended the hour-long meeting. "We are interested in rejoining. We hope the speaker will give his decision soon," said Chowdhury. Replying to a query, he said, "Although we are abstaining from jparliament, we are issuing notices regularly. But bars are being put in our way." Meanwhile, speaker Abdul Hamid has said his efforts to get the opposition to parliament are continuing. He told bdnews24.com that he had spoken with Faruk and assured him that BNP's demands would be "taken care of" in consultation with the treasury bench. "I have talked to the chief whip of the opposition regarding BNP's return to the House," Hamid said Sunday morning at his office. "I have assured them that I will look into their demands in consultation with the ruling party." Hamid also spoke with chief whip of the ruling party Abdus Shahid on bringing the BNP back to parliament. bdnews24.c
